    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-01-14T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-01-14T06:00:00-05:00" n="647"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d647">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/450: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-14T19:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 14, 1938—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 14—4:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>78. Minister of Finance<note n="37" xml:id="d647fn37">H. H. Kung.</note> has
                    telegraphed Inspector General of Customs expressing appreciation of efforts of
                    the commissioners concerned in maintaining the <hi rend="italic">status quo</hi>
                    of the Tientsin and Chinwangtao customs but stating that, (1), no orders should
                    be accepted from and no agreement of any kind should be negotiated and concluded
                    with <pb facs="0635" n="631" xml:id="pg_631"/> the bogus government; (2), no
                    changes should be made in the present customs system rules and regulations; (3),
                    present tariffs should not be revised without authority, these three conditions
                    being the minimum that should be held in maintaining the Customs Administration
                    and under no circumstances be compromised. Commissioners of Customs to be
                    instructed accordingly.</p>
                <p>2. Inspector General has replied that the commissioners are being instructed,
                    that no written agreement whatever has been made with the bogus government, that
                    in order to maintain sovereign rights and credit at home and abroad by
                    preserving the integrity of the service as the Government’s agents throughout
                    China, et cetera, it may become advisable at some ports to yield to <hi
                        rend="italic">force majeure</hi> in nonessentials, and that to stimulate
                    trade and help revive economic conditions seriously upset by hostilities, the
                    Inspector General may later submit some tariff proposals for approval of the
                    Government.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Hankow and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
